di Gras, Latino construction workers living in their trucks. As a lawyer-activist who has devoted his life to procuring justice for some of society's most disenfranchised citizens, Sothern offers a powerful vision of what Katrina has meant to New Orleans and what it still means to the nation at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDisaster victimszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aEmergency managementxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005. 0aHurricaneszLouisianazNew Orleans. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aapocalypse.  aclass war.  aclimate change.  adisenfranchisement.  aenvironmental activism.  aflooding.  airanian.  alatin americans.  alatino.  alatinx.  alevy break.  alouisiana.  amardi gras.  amiddle eastern author.  anatural disaster.  anatural disasters.  anew orleans.  apost apocalyptic scenario.  apost-katrina.  arace and racism.  asouthern cities.  atrailer park.  auniversity textbook.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093384240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933842/original  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles